ProMED-mail
e-mail: promed@usa.healthnet.org
[The claim that the Tasmanian epidemic is not influenza, but something that
"closely resemble[s] influenza", should probably at this point be taken
with a grain of salt, since major influenza A Sydney (H3N2) epidemics are
occurring elsewhere in Australia and in New Zealand and (possibly) Pohnpei.
Influenza symptoms and signs vary widely, especially in the very young and
the very old, so that it is possible to have many sequential cases without
seeing a "classical" clinical picture. Hospital
epidemics of influenza A are common, and nursing home epidemics even more
so. The latter may or may not include staff epidemics. Severe illnesses
and deaths are common even in vaccinated elderly institutionalized
patients. In addition to influenza A, influenza B and respiratory syncytial
virus may
both cause nursing home outbreaks featuring severe and fatal infections in
the elderly and debilitated. - Mod.DM]
